title: For Sale:  Norinco 56S XXX'd out NHM90
postcontent: Very interesting piece of history. This is a de-banned Norinco NHM90 that started life as a pre-ban 56S (Triangle 56 Factory rifle. Polytech Factory). The rifle was caught up in customs at the beginning of the import ban in 1990 hence the birth of the post ban NHM90. (Norinco 56S xxx'd out NHM90) The NHM90's still possessed a threaded barrel that was covered in a barrel cap and came with the hideous thumb hole stock's. This rifle has had the furniture swapped with the correct Chinese wood and the barrel cap has been removed and correct slant brake has been added with the detente pin still intact. Comes with one magazine and original Chinese sling. The rifle was a 56S built rifle and shares the 1.5mm thick receiver and heavy chrome lined barrel. Just like the Mak 90's and Polytech rifles. You will never get closer to the real thing.

postcontent: WW2 M1 Carbine manufactured by the IBM Corporation. IBM-made M1 Carbines have long been sought after for a variety of reasons, one of them being the nostalgia that a company that ended up being known world-wide for making computers actually made carbines for the war effort. This M1 Carbine is original and (mostly) correct WW2 IBM U.S. M1 Carbine .30 Caliber carbine that was brought home by a returning WWII veteran.This Carbine comes with the original IBM "SY-B" marked magazine that was in the rifle when I obtained it. I added the reproduction sling (marked JT&L 1942), the M1 Carbine magazine stock pouch (marked JT&L 1942), the Inland oiler which is marked with "II" (International Silver Co. made Oilers for most of the Prime M1 Carbine Contractors and marked them individually for each Contractor), with two unissued USGI 15 round magazines for the stock magazine pouch that are still wrapped in their original oiled paper wrappers, and an additional single 30 round magazine (marked only with "Made in U.S.A.").
